## Interaction State Pattern
All interactive components must manage hover and active states 
internally using useState and mouse/focus event handlers.

## Standard Implementation
```tsx
const [interactionStatus, setInteractionStatus] = useState(status);

// Always respect disabled — never apply hover or active to disabled
const handleMouseEnter = () => {
  if (status === 'disabled') return;
  setInteractionStatus('hover');
};

const handleMouseLeave = () => {
  if (status === 'disabled') return;
  setInteractionStatus(status);
};

const handleMouseDown = () => {
  if (status === 'disabled') return;
  setInteractionStatus('active');
};

const handleMouseUp = () => {
  if (status === 'disabled') return;
  setInteractionStatus(status);
};
```

## Rules
- Never apply hover or active states when status is 'disabled'
- interactionStatus drives visual rendering
- External status prop drives error, success, disabled states
- onMouseEnter → hover
- onMouseLeave → reset to status prop
- onMouseDown → active
- onMouseUp → reset to status prop
- Always attach handlers to the outermost interactive element